  "prompt": "What is the difference between home board and normal boards for CBSE class 10? Which one do you prefer?",
  "response": "The Central Board of Secondary Education (CBSE) in India offers students the option to take their Class 10 examinations under two different systems: the **Home Board** and the **Normal Board**. Here's the difference between the two:\n\n### 1. **Home Board (School-Based Examination)**\n   - The Home Board system allows students to take their Class 10 exams in their own school.\n   - The question papers are prepared by the school, and the evaluation is also done internally by the school teachers.\n   - This system was introduced to reduce stress and pressure on students.\n   - The Home Board exam results are often used for internal assessments and promotions to the next class.\n   - The CBSE does not issue a certificate for Home Board exams, as it is not an external examination.\n\n### 2. **Normal Board (External Examination)**\n   - The Normal Board system involves students taking their Class 10 exams in an external examination center designated by the CBSE.\n   - The question papers are prepared and distributed by the CBSE, and the evaluation is done by external examiners.\n   - This system is more formal and rigorous, and the results are considered for issuing the CBSE Class 10 certificate.\n   - The Normal Board exams are considered the standard and traditional method of assessment for Class 10.\n\n### Which One to Prefer?\n- If your goal is to obtain a CBSE Class 10 certificate, you must opt for the **Normal Board** examination.\n- If you are looking for a less stressful environment and are confident in your school's internal evaluation process, the **Home Board** system might be preferable.\n- Most students and parents prefer the **Normal Board** system because it is widely recognized and essential for future academic and professional pursuits.\n\nUltimately, the choice depends on your personal goals, comfort level, and the importance you place on formal certification.",
